<br>
Sleeper Tomb Rotation<br>
<br>
With the recent changes to the zone formerlly known as &quot;Sleeper's Tomb&quot;, the status of the rotation in regards to the mobs contained within that zone has been in question lately.  Several of the guilds on the rotation had a discussion about how the rotation should continue in the future.  This text will detail the results of the discussion, so that all guilds that are on the rotation can be made aware of the changes, and request other changes if they are not in full agreement with what is detailed here.  This text is being written from the best of my memory and may contain errors, if there are any please let me know so that I can correct them before these rules are fully in effect.<br>
<br>
Joining the rotation:<br>
To join the rotation a guild need to kill the first named mobs in the zone.  These are Master of the Gaurd and The Progenitor.  Once a guild has killed they two mobs they will be given a normal place on the Sleeper's Tomb rotation.  (All guilds on the current ST rotation will be given a chance to kill these mobs in thier normal rotation order.  If they fail to kill the mobs a few times then they will probably be asked to remove themselved from the rotation.)<br>
<br>
Being on the rotation:<br>
Having a place on the ST rotation ensures that you get a chance to clear all the mobs in the zone once per turn.  (Time between turns determined by how many guilds are on the rotation.)  During your turn you may kill any mob within the zone that you can (including Golems, Minis, Ancients, and Milas).  If you are unable to kill all of the named mobs within the zone you are required to inform the guild up on the Ancients rotation.<br>
<br>
<br>
Ancients Rotation:<br>
<br>
Joining the rotation:<br>
To join the Ancients rotation a guild must kill all of the Ancients in one clearing.  (I.E. You can't kill 2 of them one clearing, and the other 2 the next clearing.)  When a guild kills all of the Ancients they will be added to the rotation in the last position, just ahead of the guild currently up for the rotation. <br>
<br>
Being on the rotation:<br>
Having a place on the Ancients rotation gives a guild a &quot;clean up&quot; position in ST.  After the guild up for the ST rotation leaves the zone any mobs that they can not kill go to the guild on the Ancients rotation.  This rotation is called &quot;Ancients rotation&quot; basically because &quot;ST clean up rotation&quot; sounds dumb.  If the guild that is up for the ST rotation clears the full zone, then nothing happens to the Ancients rotation.  The same guild is still up for next clean up.  Clearing the zone when you are up for the ST rotation does not effect the Ancients rotation at all.  If a guild is up for both rotations and clears the zone, then the ST rotation advances while they remain up for the next clean up. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><br><font color=#00FFFF>- </font><a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/btherathetravelagency>The Rathe Travel Agency Board</a><font color=#00FFFF> - </font><a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ftherathetravelagencyfrm52>Rathe Etiquette </a> <font color=#00FFFF> - </font><a href="http://www.jakefitch.com/rta/Calendar.asp">The Rathe Calendar</a><font color=#00FFFF> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.102<br>Copyright ©1999-2002 ezboard, Inc.<br>Accelerated By <a href="http://www.wbs.com/ezboard.html">JXEL</a></center></body></html>  

